1 Data

The dataset here used comes from High-STEACS (High Sensitivity Troponin in the Evaluation of patients with suspected Acute Coronary Syndrome) trial.

1.1 Pre-processing

We load available data and filter type 2 MI events only. The analysed dataset contains 1121 patients.

data.path   <- file.path("//farr-fs1/Study Data/LOT-16-001/Research",
                          "High-STEACS/HS006_BHF-Turing/KarlaMonterrubio")
data        <- readRDS(file.path(data.path, "Data_analysis.Rds"))

ct.master   <- readRDS(file.path(data.path,"TypeII_MI/ct.master.hs.data.rds")) #ct.master contains variables not included in data, and which will be used for the analysis
names(ct.master)[names(ct.master)=="patientid"] <- "PatientId"
ct.master.tomerge <- ct.master[, c("PatientId","type1ortype4bmi1", "type1ortype4bmidate", 
                                     "mechanism", "arrival_date", "cardiovasculardeathdate")]
data_TypeII <- merge(data,ct.master.tomerge , by="PatientId")
data_TypeII <- subset(data_TypeII, udmi4=="Type 2 MI")

Now, let’s select the clinical covariates that we will be using.

covariates <- c("PatientId", "AGE_ON_ARRIVAL", "SEX_CODE_LOC", "PeakHSTn",
                "haemoglobinvalue","PrevHFHospitalisation", "PrevCD",
                "PrevDiabetes", "PrevIHD",  "MyocardialIschemia",
                "prim_out", "outcomedate_prim", "non_cardio_death", "days.to.mace.death.followup",
                "DaysFromIndexAdmission", "arrival_date", "type1ortype4bmidate",
                "cardiovasculardeathdate", "CreatinineValue", "PrevMI","SystolicBP", "HeartRate")
data_TypeII_clinical <- data_TypeII[ , covariates]
colnames(data_TypeII_clinical) <- c("PatientID","Age","Sex","PeakTroponin",
                                    "Haemoglobin","PrevHFHospitalisation","PrevCD",
                                   "PrevDiabetes", "PrevIHD", "MyocardialIschemia",
                                   "secondary_outcome","outcomedate_secout",
                                    "non_cardio_death", "days.to.mace.death.followup",
                                   "DaysFromIndexAdmission", "arrival_date",
                                   "type1ortype4bmidate", "cardiovasculardeathdate", "CreatinineValue",
                                   "PrevMI","SystolicBP", "HeartRate")

We will compute eGFR based on MDRD equation using available covariates: creatinine, age and sex.

data_TypeII_clinical$eGFR<- round(186*((data_TypeII_clinical$CreatinineValue/88.42)^-1.154)*
                                              data_TypeII_clinical$Age^-0.203*
                                              ifelse(data_TypeII_clinical$Sex=="F",0.742,1 ))

#Mark eGFR as NA when CreatinineValue is either NA or 0.
pos.creatzero <- which(data_TypeII_clinical$CreatinineValue==0)
data_TypeII_clinical$eGFR[pos.creatzero] <- NA

We employ Haemoglobin and Sex to define a new covariate of interest: Anaemia. Following the defition of the WHO, this is derived as:

  • For male: Haemoglobin < 130 then Anaemia = Yes; otherwise Anaemia = No
  • For female: Haemoglobin < 120 then Anaemia = Yes; otherwise Anaemia = No
 data_TypeII_clinical$Anaemia <- NA 
 data_TypeII_clinical$Anaemia <- ifelse(data_TypeII_clinical$Sex=="F",
                                ifelse(data_TypeII_clinical$Haemoglobin<120, "Yes", "No"),
                                ifelse(data_TypeII_clinical$Haemoglobin<130, "Yes", "No")) 
 
 data_TypeII_clinical$Anaemia <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$Anaemia)
 data_TypeII_clinical$Anaemia <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$Anaemia, ref= "No")

Now, we derive time to event variables for each of the events of interest:

  • Primary outcome: MI or all cause death at 365 days
  • Secondary outcome: MI or cardiovascular death at 365 days
#compute the days to event for MI
data_TypeII_clinical$MI_days <- as.numeric(round(difftime(data_TypeII_clinical$type1ortype4bmidate, data_TypeII_clinical$arrival_date, units = "days")))
data_TypeII_clinical$MI_days[is.na(data_TypeII_clinical$MI_days)==TRUE] <- 365

#time to cardiovascular death
data_TypeII_clinical$Cardio_days <- as.numeric(round(difftime(data_TypeII_clinical$cardiovasculardeathdate, data_TypeII_clinical$arrival_date, units = "days")))
data_TypeII_clinical$Cardio_days[is.na(data_TypeII_clinical$Cardio_days)==TRUE] <- 365

#Time for secondary outcome. Note, we are rounding numerically.
data_TypeII_clinical$Secout_days <- pmin(data_TypeII_clinical$MI_days, data_TypeII_clinical$Cardio_days)


#Status=1 secondary out, status=2 non_cardio death, status =0 censored.
data_TypeII_clinical$status <- ifelse(data_TypeII_clinical$secondary_outcome==1,1,  
                               ifelse(data_TypeII_clinical$non_cardio_death==1,2,0))

#time for Competing events
data_TypeII_clinical$timetoevent_cr <- data_TypeII_clinical$Secout_days
pos_CR <- which(data_TypeII_clinical$status == 2)
data_TypeII_clinical$timetoevent_cr[pos_CR] <- data_TypeII_clinical$DaysFromIndexAdmission[pos_CR]


#days to all-cause death or MI
data_TypeII_clinical$days_MIorALLCAUSE <- pmin(data_TypeII_clinical$MI_days,data_TypeII_clinical$DaysFromIndexAdmission)

#indicator for all-cause death or MI
data_TypeII_clinical$MIorAllcausedeath <- rep(0, nrow(data_TypeII_clinical))
pos_MI <- which(is.na(data_TypeII_clinical$type1ortype4bmidate)==FALSE)
data_TypeII_clinical$MIorAllcausedeath[pos_MI] <- 1
pos_deaths <- which(data_TypeII_clinical$DaysFromIndexAdmission<365)
data_TypeII_clinical$MIorAllcausedeath[pos_deaths] <- 1

Now, we mark as factor all discrete variables. In addition, we change 1 and 2 for Yes and No to be more explicit. Also, we set No as reference for all binary varibles.

data_TypeII_clinical$PrevHFHospitalisation <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevHFHospitalisation)
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevDiabetes <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevDiabetes)
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevIHD <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevIHD)
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevMI <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevMI)
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevCD <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevCD)
data_TypeII_clinical$MyocardialIschemia <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$MyocardialIschemia)
data_TypeII_clinical$Sex <- as.factor(data_TypeII_clinical$Sex)

data_TypeII_clinical$PrevDiabetes <- recode_factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevDiabetes, `1`="Yes", '2'="No")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevIHD  <- recode_factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevIHD,`1`="Yes", '2'="No") 
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevMI <- recode_factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevMI, `1`="Yes", '2'="No")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevHFHospitalisation  <- recode_factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevHFHospitalisation,`1`="Yes", '2'="No") 
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevCD <- recode_factor(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevCD, `1`="Yes", '2'="No")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevIHD <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevIHD, ref="No")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevDiabetes <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevDiabetes, ref="No")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevHFHospitalisation <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevHFHospitalisation, ref="No")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevCD <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevCD, ref = "No")
data_TypeII_clinical$MyocardialIschemia <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$MyocardialIschemia, ref= "No")
data_TypeII_clinical$Sex <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$Sex, ref = "M")
data_TypeII_clinical$PrevMI <- relevel(data_TypeII_clinical$PrevMI, ref = "No")

We will not consider SystolicBP in our model because the proportion of missing values is very high (37.5%). However, for the other covariates that have missing values we will use imputation.

In order to impute missing values, we use mice R package with predicting mean matching (pmm). This method works for both continuous and discrete covariates, ensuring that the imputed values have a similar distribution as those observed, and as such it won’t produce imputed values outside the range of the observed data. In addition, pmm is known for being robust to transformations (eg. log).

set.seed(40)
cov_impute <- c("Age", "Sex","PeakTroponin", "PrevHFHospitalisation", "Haemoglobin","PrevDiabetes",
                "PrevIHD","PrevCD","MyocardialIschemia","eGFR", "HeartRate")

imputed_data <- mice(data_TypeII_clinical[ ,cov_impute], m = 5, maxit = 50, method = "pmm",seed = 500)

data_TypeII_imputed1 <- complete(imputed_data,2)
data_typeII_imputed <- data.frame(cbind(data_TypeII_clinical$PatientID, 
                                        data_TypeII_imputed1,
                                        data_TypeII_clinical[, c("Secout_days", "secondary_outcome",
                                                                 "status","timetoevent_cr",
                                                                 "days_MIorALLCAUSE",
                                                                 "MIorAllcausedeath" )]))

Once, we have imputed the dataset, we employ Haemoglobin and Sex to define Anaemia. This is defined as:

 data_typeII_imputed$Anaemia <- NA
 data_typeII_imputed$Anaemia <- ifelse(data_typeII_imputed$Sex=="F",
                                ifelse(data_typeII_imputed$Haemoglobin<120, "Yes", "No"),
                                ifelse(data_typeII_imputed$Haemoglobin<130, "Yes", "No"))

 data_typeII_imputed$Anaemia <- as.factor(data_typeII_imputed$Anaemia)

data_TypeII_imputed <- data_typeII_imputed
colnames(data_TypeII_imputed)[1]<- "PatientId"

2.2 Multivariate CPH

Now, we fit a multivariate CPH. The selected covariates corresponds to:

  • Age,
  • eGFR,
  • Logarithm of troponin,
  • Anaemia,
  • Myocardial ischaemia,
  • Previous heart failure hospitalisation,
  • Previous diabetes,
  • Previous ischaemic heart disease, and
  • Heart rate

Due to violation of the linearity assumption for Age, eGFR and Heart rate, we employ restricted cubic splines with 4, 3, and 3 knots, respectively. Location of the knots is determine internally by the rcs( ) function (employing quantiles).

2.2.1 Validation

In this section we present internal validation - calibration and discrimination.

A calibration plot for the survival probability at 365 days is obtained. The diagonal grey line depicts perfect calibration, the black line corresponds to apparent calibration estimated by adaptive linear spline hazard regression, and the blue line shows bootstrap (200 samples) bias-corrected calibration curve.

cal.primout <- calibrate(Cox_primout, u = 365, cmethod = "hare", B = 200, 
                         subtitles = FALSE, legend = FALSE, riskdist = FALSE )

However, for consistency with the external model evaluation, here we also provide a calibration plot for the risk. This plot is generated using pec R package, which permits to pass only the predicted probabilities instead of the whole cph object.

The first two plot assess the model on the whole training data and the second two use bootstrap cross-validation (B=200). Note also that for the smooth curve the difference with the plot above shown is the method used for estimation. The above plot uses a flexible hazard regression model to create the calibration curve and here we have used a nearest neighborhood approach.

Now that good calibration has been evaluated, we report two measures of discrimination. The first one, corresponds to the concordance or C-index:

set.seed(200)
val.internal <- validate(Cox_primout, B=200)

## [1] "Bootstraped C-statistic:"
## [1] 0.705

The second, corresponds to the AUROC (area under the receiver operating characteristic):

data_primout <- data_TypeII_imputed_reduced

s0365.30days_prim = S030days[length(S030days)]


#LPs and probability
df_type2mi_30daysevents$LP30days_prim <- predictrms(cox30days_prim, data= df_type2mi_30daysevents)
df_type2mi_30daysevents$prob.primout = 1-s0365.30days_prim^exp(df_type2mi_30daysevents$LP30days_prim) 

#roc

                              df_type2mi_30daysevents$prob.primout, 
                              auc.polygon = TRUE,
